<!-- SC_OFF --><div class="md"><p>I have a brand new install up and running on btrfs and bare metal. Before I install a desktop, or begin “playing” with this system (the primary purpose of which is to learn more about btrfs, subvolumes and snapper lol) I obviously wanted to install snapper, but I immediately receive an error message when attempting to create a snapper configuration:</p> <p><code># yay -S snapper-support</code></p> <p><code># cd /</code></p> <p><code># snapper -c root create-config /</code></p> <p><code>Creating config failed (subvolume already covered).</code></p> <p>Covered? Covered by what? What does this mean? I ddg&#39;d this error message and I found a single reference to, &quot;<strong><em>already covered</em></strong>&quot; <a href="https://bbs.archlinux.org/viewtopic.php?id=273890">https://bbs.archlinux.org/viewtopic.php?id=273890</a></p> <p>This message suggests that removing both the &#39;@snapshots subvolume and the /.snapshots directory should fix the problem. I first deleted the directory, which didn&#39;t help and then I deleted the subvolume, which also didn&#39;t help. I still can&#39;t create a snapper configuration.</p> <p>I did a <code># pacman -Rns</code> and then reinstalled snapper-support, but I get the same error when attempting to create a new configuration. As I already mentioned, I tried deleting the /.snapshots directory and subvolume and I&#39;m out of ideas because I still have no idea what &quot;<em>already covered</em>&quot; means, so I&#39;m groping in the dark. I&#39;ve read through the Arch wiki and creating the default snapper configuration is literally step one! So, I have no idea how I immediately got off track. Any suggestions would be welcome and thanks in advance!</p> <p>Some system background info (prior to the deletions):</p> <p><code># btrfs subvol list /</code></p> <p><code>ID 256 gen 233 top level 5 path @</code></p> <p><code>ID 257 gen 225 top level 5 path @cache</code></p> <p><code>ID 258 gen 225 top l